1) write a java program to divide two numbers entered by the user. use try-catch to handle arithmeticexception (divide by zero)
import java.util.Scanner;

public class DivideNumbers {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter the numerator: ");
        int numerator = sc.nextInt();

        System.out.print("Enter the denominator: ");
        int denominator = sc.nextInt();

        try {
            int result = numerator / denominator;
            System.out.println("Result: " + result);
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Error: Cannot divide by zero!");
        }
    }
}


2)create:parent class product with a constructor that sets productld, subclass electronics with warrentyand its own showdetails(), use super() to call parent constructor and super.showdetaild() inside overridden method.
// Parent class
class Product {
    protected int productId;

    // Constructor that sets productId
    public Product(int productId) {
        this.productId = productId;
    }

    // Parent method to be overridden
    public void showDetails() {
        System.out.println("Product ID: " + productId);
    }
}

// Subclass
class Electronics extends Product {
    private int warrantyYears;

    // Constructor using super() to call parent constructor
    public Electronics(int productId, int warrantyYears) {
        super(productId);
        this.warrantyYears = warrantyYears;
    }

    // Overridden method with super.showDetails()
    @Override
    public void showDetails() {
        super.showDetails();  // Call parent version
        System.out.println("Warranty (years): " + warrantyYears);
    }
}

// Demo class
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Electronics e = new Electronics(2001, 3);
        e.showDetails();
    }
}
